More than just a laser scope, the LG-ND3 Laser Illuminator combines a powerful, green laser light diode and a precision optical collimator. Pair the ND3 Laser Genetics Light with your rifle scope and you can cast a bright beam of green laser light to fully illuminate targets up to 250 yards. The patented optical collimator allows for quick, one hand, full range adjustment of beam diameter and light strength with just 180 degrees of rotation. With this powerful, easy to use green laser flashlight, you never have to take your eyes off the target, or your hand off the trigger.
The Laser Genetics ND3 Laser Designator features a system of 9 fully multi-coated lenses, and a patented Rotary Optical Collimator that allows full adjustment and control of beam diameter and intensity to focus light where you need it most. Rotating the collimator ring to minimum creates a bright micro beam of green laser light visible up to 3 miles. Rotating collimator to a more open setting provides plenty of illumination to light a trail at night or paint a target at 250 yards. Battery life allows you to handle a variety of emergencies with over 7 hours of available power. The ND3 Laser Designator from Laser Genetics works well for both night hunting and game spotting. For optimum night vision for hunting, pair the Laser Genetics ND-3 Green Laser Sight with a high quality variable power riflescope having a 40mm or larger objective lens providing maximum light transmission. The included ND3 mounting system for 1" tubes provides full adjustment for windage and elevation for scope alignment. Additional mounts for binocular, spotting scopes and weaver rails are included.
The Laser Genetics ND Series of Laser Designators features low energy use and high illumination yield, enabling you to focus full illumination where you need it, with the least loss of light due to "flooding". The ND Series puts you in full control of directed laser light for maximum illumination of the intended object. The high power laser beam may be collimated down and concentrated to cast an intense, highly visible beam of light that can be seen miles away, useful for signaling or search and rescue operations. Or adjust the beam to 10ft to light a path for full night vision. Green light is the most visible to the human eye and requires the least amount of eye adjustment at night. High power green laser light reflects intensely off the eyes of animals allowing quick detection up to 250 yards.
Laser Genetics specializes in green laser sights, lights and scopes specific for outdoors, hunting, marine, emergency, and home defense use. Laser Genetics utilizes exclusive patented optical laser technology to develop the lighting instruments of the future for civilian and professional use. FL selbstlader drgm .32 dose not have a clip found one online for $36 here some info on it Langenhan Army Model pistol (a.k.a. F.L. Selbstlader Model I). It was produced by Friedrich Langenhan in Zelia Mehlis, Germany. This was a blowback-operated semiautomatic pistol chambered in .32 ACP. It has a 4" barrel and a detachable 8-shot magazine. The pistol was made with a separate breechblock that is held into the slide by a screw. This pistol was produced and used in WWI only, from 1915-1918, and was never offered commercially. It is marked "F.L. Selbstlade DRGM". The finish is blued with "F.L." at the top. Estimate value: $250 - 400 at a gun shop 300 bro

For sale is one Beretta M9 in NRA Excellent Condition with 4 magazines, 1 Serpa Blackhawk OWB holster and Hogue grips. This pistol is a police trade-in, but is in great shape, and shows little use outside of holster wear from daily carry.

Finish is 95 percent blue with honest holster wear and small white patches around the muzzle, front of the slide and safety/decocker. Rifling is bright, sharp and shiny and shows some wear, but is in great shape. The frame has stock "combat" style sights, which are quick to get on target, but not great for precision shots. I personally have a preference for S&B and PPU, but the pistol seems to function flawlessly with all types of ball ammunition. I've not used is as a carry gun, so I have no experience with defense loads.

I've had some work done to the trigger; it has a very crisp single action pull, and a tolerable double action, which is a vast improvement over the stock 15lb+ DA pull.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Baby Browning .25ACP * RARE ?? *
postcontent:
Info on standard FN/Baby Browning 25s is easy enough to find but this one is a little different.  It has a single line "Fabrique National" on the slide, Browining on the grips, NO proof marks - inside or out.  Note the unusual serial number 00C0000XXX.  Mine is identical to the picture (thanks to J. Zachary for the use of his blog pic).

I am confident that it is NOT one of the original Belgian produced, or French (MAB) produced pieces, there are NO proof marks.  The serial number does not fit any to the easy to find sequences. The piece and packing are not age appropriate for this either. 

I am also certain its NOT a LATER PSA production as it does not bear the the "Virginia" stamp on the slide and the serial number does not begin with "VA".

I thinking its a really early PSP/PSA piece produced in Colorado. 

I have exhausted all the books and web pages I can find. Any information on this little mystery would be much appreciated.

** Many thanks to those who have provided information!! **
